surveys.narrative:
Typo is a shallow lake (maximum depth 5 ft) prone to winterkill, and is part of the Sunrise River system. Walleye, Black Crappie, White Crappie, Northern Pike, and Bluegill are the most abundant gamefish in Typo Lake, and Walleye are the primary management species on Typo Lake with 295,000 fry stocked in odd numbered years.

Twenty two Walleyes were sampled in gill nets at a rate of 11 per net. This is below the rate of 21 per net recorded in the last gill net survey in 1999, but still above average for Typo lake. Black Crappies were sampled at rate of 29.5 per net in the gill nets and 2.2 per net in the trap nets. White Crappie were sampled at a rate of 1 fish per net in the gill nets and 3.33 fish per net in the trap nets. These rates are average to above average for both species. Northern Pike were sampled at a rate of 7.5 per gill net. This is a significant increase from the last gillnet survey in 1999, and pike over 30 inches were sampled.

Typo Lake is managed for walleyes with biannual fry stocking. The walleye population has increased dramatically (21/gillnet) since the last netting in 1995 (3.5/gillnet). Lengths ranged from 8.4 to 24.3 inches with a 14.8 inch average. Black and white crappie are present in moderate to high numbers. Lengths for both species ranged from about 4.5 to 13.2 inches. Black crappies averaged 8.6 inches and white crappies averaged 9.5 inches. Twelve inch plus fish were sampled for both crappie species, but were relatively sparse. Bluegill are present in moderate numbers, with lengths between 4.4 and 8.6 inches and a 6.4 inch average. Northern pike were sampled in moderate numbers with lengths ranging from 13.5 to 24.8 inches. Black bullhead were abundant and averaged about 9 inches long. Common carp were very abundant and averaged about 13.5 inches. Yellow perch have been sampled in low to moderate past nettings, but only one was caught in 1999.

Blk Crappies/Blk Bullheads-abv avg. num. while the rest of the species were blw avg. num. This is due to partial and complete winter experimented in '61-62, 63-64, & 71-72. A prtl wntkl was also experienced dur. this wntr. This will probably favor the already hgh Blhd pop. Blk Crappies and Blk Bullheads were the only species of lrgr fish which had any natural reproduction.

Black crappies were the most abundant species sampled during the assessment. White crappies were also very numerous. Both species were sampled at record levels for Typo Lake. Crappies over 10 inches in length were sampled. Black bullhead numbers continue to decline in the lake. The 2010 survey sampled 0.33 black bullheads per set which is the lowest catch recorded in the lake. Bluegills were found at their highest abundance for this lake. The average length sampled was 6.7 inches. Northern pike and walleye were sampled in low abundance.

BROWN BULLHEAD, YELLOW BULLHEAD, YELLOW PERCH, PUMPKINSEED, BLUEGILL, AND HYBRID SUNFISH WERE FOUND AT BELOW LOCAL MEDIAN LEVELS. WHITE SUCKER, CARP, BLACK BULLHEAD, WALLEYE, AND BLACK CRAPPIES WERE FOUND AT ABOVE LOCAL MEDIAN NUMBERS. THE FISH POPULATION OF TYPO LAKE IS DOMINATED BY ROUGHFISH. NORTHERN PIKE ARE PRESENT IN THE LAKE. CARP HAVE REMAINED RELATIVELY STABLE SINCE 1979. WALLEYES ARE MOST LIKELY FROM IN-MIGRATION FROM MARTIN LAKE WHERE FRY HAVE BEEN STOCKED. BLACK CRAPPIES SHOW A GOOD SIZE DISTRIBUTION. WINTERKILLS ALLOWS FOR GROWTH.

Black bullhead and carp were the most abundant species captured, with numbers of each far above the average for this type of lake. Crappies and sunfish species were sampled in moderate to low numbers with fish of good average size. Northern pike were common with most fish weighing two pounds or less. Walleye numbers were low with all fish of acceptable size to anglers.

Black bullhead continue to be the most abundant species found in Typo Lake but their numbers have dropped since the previous survey. Black crappies were the second most abundant species. Their numbers are also down since the last survey, but are still within the normal range for this type of lake. Crappies up to 15 inches were sampled. Bluegills were sampled in their highest abundace during the survey. The average length sampled was 7.5 inches. Over 80% of the bluegills captured exceeded 7 inches. Northern pike were taken in low numbers and were of average size. Walleyes numbers were low but those sampled were of a size anglers prefer.
